'''Gerardus "Gerard" Brackx''' (1931, [[Ostend]] – 19 September 2011<ref>{{cite news |title=Oprichter Jetair Gerard Brackx overleden |url= http://www.tijd.be/nieuws/ondernemingen_toerisme/Oprichter_Jetair_Gerard_Brackx_overleden.9105897-3077.art?ckc=1 |agency= [[Belga (news agency)|Belga]] |newspaper= [[De Tijd]] |date= 19 September 2011|accessdate= 20 November 2011|language= Dutch |trans-title=Jetair founder Gerard Brackx has died}}</ref>) was a [[Belgium|Belgian]] businessman, pioneer of the Belgian [[tourism|travel business]] and founder of [[TUI AG|Jetair]]. His father was a [[Catholic]] businessman who owned a factory which produced [[washing machine]]s and [[bicycle]]s. Gerard was the seventh child out of nine. On the verge of World War II, his father died of [[pneumonia]] and Gerard had to start help working at the age of 16 to earn money for his family.
==Career== At the age of 24, after finishing school and serving in the army (part of which he spent in [[Kassel]], [[Germany]]), he dreamt of a future in [[car]]s and [[tourism|travel]]. He married Diane Provoost, whose father had a garage where he started his career as a [[salesman]]. He worked there for five years when he saw the first [[bus]]ses appear in the garage. In 1956, together with his brother-in-law, Roger Provoost, he started organizing bus travels during the summer months (when the buses stood idle) through ''Reiskantoren Royal Tours'' for [[United Kingdom|British]] tourists visiting the Belgian coast. In addition he started offering tours for [[Flemish people|Fleming]]s to the English coast across the [[English Channel]].
In 1958, with the [[Expo '58|Brussels World’s Fair]] came the breakthrough and in addition he started offering journeys to [[Lourdes]], [[German Tyrol|Tyrol]] and the [[Costa Brava]]. At the end of the sixties, he was the first Belgian tour operator who offered organised air travel in association with [[Sabena]] to [[Benidorm]] (Spain). For many years he would be known as ''Mijnheer Benidorm ''(Mister Benidorm) as he discovered Benidorm as a vacation resort during the sixties. In 1970, he opened his own Hotel Belroy in Benidorm and until 1978 would remain the only Belgian tour operator who offered flight vacations to Benidorm. In 1996, he sold Jetair to the German travel organization [[TUI AG|Touristik Union International (TUI)]].
During his last years, Brackx occupied himself with the [[real estate]] of the family holding Immobra.<ref>{{cite news|title=Gerard Brackx |url=http://trends.knack.be/economie/archief-trends/widget-1184709444473.htm?articleID=206138# |newspaper=Trends/Cash |date=26 April 2011 |accessdate=20 November 2011 |language=Dutch |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120215092636/http://trends.knack.be/economie/archief-trends/widget-1184709444473.htm?articleID=206138 |archivedate=15 February 2012 |df=dmy }}</ref> He died in Ostend on 19 September 2011, aged 80 and was buried there on 24 September.
