{{Infobox person |name = Rod Kenyon |honorific_suffix = {{postnominals|country=GBR|size=100%|OBE}} |image = |alt = |caption = |birth_name = Rodney Frank Kenyon |birth_date = {{Birth year|1945}} |birth_place = |death_date = {{death date and age |2013|12|8 |1945|6 |df=yes}} |death_place = |other_names = | party = [[Social Democratic Party (UK)|SDP]] |known_for = Gas Industry Education and Training |occupation = Human Resource Director |nationality = British }}
'''Rodney Frank Kenyon''' {{postnominals|country=GBR|OBE|FCIS}} (June 1945 – 8 December 2013)<ref name=":0">{{Cite web|url=http://www.skills2learn.com/news.php?art=85|title=E-learning and learning solution news from Skills2Learn|website=www.skills2learn.com|access-date=2016-12-31}}</ref> was a former Human Resources Director at British Gas and was Director of the [[British Gas Engineering Academy]].<ref name="uwl">http://www.uwl.ac.uk/the_university/how_the_university_works/profiles/rod_kenyon.jsp University of West London - Profiles</ref> In 2001, he was a Director of the [[Apprenticeship Ambassadors Network]].<ref name="uwl" />
Kenyon was also Vice Chairman of [[Energy and Utility Skills]] and former [[Chairman]] of [[Learning and Skills Council]] Region Council for London.<ref name="uwl" /> Kenyon was appointed to the board of the [[University of West London]] in 2001.<ref name="uwl" />
He was a Trustee of [[the National Gas Museum Trust]]<ref>http://www.charity-commission.gov.uk/Showcharity/RegisterOfCharities/ContactAndTrustees.aspx?RegisteredCharityNumber=1072375&SubsidiaryNumber=0&TID=2195857 Charity 1072375</ref> and a Director of [[Dyslexia Action]].<ref name="uwl" />
Kenyon contested the UK parliamentary [[constituency]] of [[Houghton and Washington East (UK Parliament constituency)|Houghton and Washington]] in the 1983 and 1987 [[General Elections]] as a [[Social Democratic Party (UK)|Social Democrat]] receiving 24% and 18% share of the vote respectively. In 1985 he contested the [[Tyne Bridge by-election, 1985|Tyne Bridge by-election]] for the [[SDP-Liberal Alliance]] finishing second to [[David Clelland]].
Kenyon was appointed an [[Officer of the Order of the British Empire]] (OBE) in the [[2005 Birthday Honours]] for services to the Energy Industry.<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=57665 |date=11 June 2005 | page=11|supp=y}}</ref>
Kenyon died 8 December 2013, aged 68.<ref name=":0" /><ref>{{cite news|title=Rodney Kenyon|url=https://www.thegazette.co.uk/notice/L-60806-2012766|accessdate=27 July 2017|work=The London Gazette|date=13 March 2014}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.euskills.co.uk/tribute-rod-kenyon-obe|title=A Tribute to Rod Kenyon OBE {{!}} Energy & Utility Skills|website=www.euskills.co.uk|access-date=2016-12-31}}</ref> a
