{{third-party|date=April 2017}} {{Infobox award | name = The Stevie Awards | image = The Stevie Awards.png | description = Excellence in [[Business]] | country = International | sponsor = American Business Awards | year = 2002 | website = {{URL|http://www.stevieawards.com/|stevieawards.com}} }}
'''The Stevie Awards''' are a set of hundreds of business awards given annually by the American Business Awards organization. They were created in 2002 to recognize accomplishments and contributions of companies and business people worldwide. The 2002 awards were called ''The American Business Awards''; the 2003, ''The International Business Awards'', since then the present title has been used. Approximately 30-40% of entrants receive an award.
==History== Michael P. Gallagher, an American businessman, conceived the Stevie Awards as a way to "restore public confidence and investor trust"<ref name=wapo>{{cite news|title = Fairfax Man Wants Stevie Trophy To Join Ranks of Tony and Oscar | first = Woodrow | last = Irvin | work = The Washington Post |url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-250387.html | date = March 9, 2003| page = T27}} {{subscription required|via=[[HighBeam Research]]}}.</ref> after the [[Enron scandal]] in 2001. Gallagher left his job in 2001 and founded American Business Awards to administer the Stevies.{{cn|date=September 2018}} When launched in 2002, the awards were described by the ''[[New York Post]]'' as being intended to "distinguish the good guys from the scoundrels" during a period heightened scrutiny and distrust of managers and CEOs.<ref>{{cite news|title = Good Guy Awards for CEOs – Hoping 'Oscars' Will Keep Them in Line | first = Paul | last = Tharp | date = September 22, 2002 | work = The New York Post | page = 34 |url=https://nypost.com/2002/09/22/good-guy-awards-for-ceos-hoping-oscars-will-keep-them-in-line/ | quote = CEOs will get a new chance to clean up their image with the launch of the business world's own Oscar awards.}}</ref> The first Stevies was awarded in 48 categories in April 2003<ref name=nyt>{{cite news |last=Ellin |first=Abby |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2003/04/27/business/private-sector-a-diogenes-of-wall-street-finds-executives-to-reward.html |title=A Diogenes of Wall Street Finds Executives to Reward |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=April 27, 2003 |accessdate=2014-05-27 }}</ref> and judged by a panel including [[Rich Karlgaard]], the editor of ''[[Forbes]]'' magazine and Richard Klimoski, Dean of the School of Management at [[George Mason University]].<ref name=wapo/>
==Award == Stevie is taken from the name Stephen, which is derived from the [[Greek language|Greek]] for "crowned".{{cn|date=September 2018}}
The charge to be considered for a Stevie in 2003 ranged from $200 to $400.<ref name=nyt/> As of 2014, entry fees range up to $505.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stevieawards.com/uploads/file/ABA14EntryFees.pdf|title=2014 AMERICAN BUSINESS AWARDS ENTRY FEES|publisher=Stevie Awards|accessdate=27 May 2014}}</ref> There is an additional fee for attending the awards dinner.<ref name=faq/>
Awards are judged each year by figures in business worldwide who participate in an evaluation process of nominees. Their recommendations for winners are announced at annual awards ceremonies held in New York City and other locations.<ref name=wapo/>
According to the organization, awards are given in hundreds of categories, and 30-40% of entrants receive an award.<ref name=faq>{{cite web|url=http://www.stevieawards.com/pubs/about/69_340_1416.cfm#Q25|title=FAQ|publisher=Stevie Awards|accessdate=27 May 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stevieawards.com/pubs/awards/70_816_3655.cfm|title=Categories - Stevie Awards|website=www.stevieawards.com|accessdate=29 October 2017}}</ref> In 2017, there were 14 main categories for which awards were given including: company/organization, customer service, human resources, IT, live event, management, marketing, mobile website & app, new product, public relations, publications, support, video, and website.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://stevieawards.com/aba/2017-website-award-winners|title=2017 Website Award Winners - Stevie Awards|website=stevieawards.com|accessdate=29 October 2017}}</ref>
The trophy is manufactured by [[R.S. Owens & Company|R. S. Owens]] as a 16-inch tall, hand-cast statuette finished in 24-[[Karat (purity)|karat]] [[gold]], holding a crystal pyramid representing [[Maslow's hierarchy of needs]].<ref>[https://www.stevieawards.com/pubs/sales/awards/398_2049_13360.cfm "The Stevie Awards For Sales And Customer Service"] Retrieved on 27 March 2014.</ref>{{primary inline|date=September 2018}}
